# What Linux is

Ten answers, all correct — because "Linux" names **two things**: the kernel, and the whole system built around it.

## The kernel

**Linux** is one program: the **kernel** — the software that talks to **hardware** (CPU, RAM, disk, network). Every file read, every pixel drawn, is ultimately a request to the kernel.

## The distribution

A kernel alone has **no prompt**. Wrap it in a **shell**, commands (`ls`, `cp`), and a package manager and you get a **distro** — Ubuntu, Debian, Fedora, RHEL. Same kernel underneath.

## The map (this whole course)

```
Your programs        firefox · python
Userspace tools      bash · ls · systemd
The kernel           ← "Linux"
Hardware             CPU · RAM · disk · NIC
```

**Why bother:** servers, Android, the **cloud**, containers — all Linux. Goal: **zero → LFCS**.
